---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema, medicalWebPageSchema } from '../../../../data/schema.js';

const title = '6–9 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress';
const description = 'Between 6 and 9 months, babies reach major developmental milestones including sitting without support, early babbling like "mama" and "dada," object permanence, and the beginning of solid foods.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'When do babies usually start sitting up without support?',
    answer: 'Most babies begin to sit without support between 6 and 8 months. Initially, they may use their arms for balance (the "tripod sit"), but by 9 months, many can sit steadily while playing with toys (CDC, 2022). If your baby is not sitting with help by 9 months, mention it to your pediatrician.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should my baby be crawling by 9 months?',
    answer: 'While many babies begin to crawl between 7 and 10 months, some skip crawling entirely and move straight to pulling up and cruising (CDC, 2022). The AAP focuses more on the ability to move and explore the environment rather than the specific method. As long as your baby is finding ways to get around, this is not a concern.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What sounds should my 9-month-old be making?',
    answer: 'By 9 months, most babies are babbling with repetitive strings of sounds like "bababa," "dadada," or "mamama" and may understand the word "no" (CDC, 2022). They respond to their name and may look when you call them. These repetitive syllable strings are the foundation of their first real words.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is separation anxiety normal at this age?',
    answer: 'Yes, separation anxiety often peaks between 8 and 12 months. Your baby now understands object permanence — that people exist even when they cannot see them — but lacks a mature sense of time, so your absence feels alarming (CDC, 2022). Consistent goodbye routines help them learn that you will return. This is a sign of healthy attachment.',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/6-9-months/milestones/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
const mSchema = medicalWebPageSchema({
  name: title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/6-9-months/milestones/',
});
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  medicalSchema={mSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: '6–9 Months', href: '/ages/6-9-months/' },
    { label: 'Milestones' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>6–9 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress</h1>

  <p>The window between 6 and 9 months is a period of incredible physical and social expansion. Your baby is transitioning from a stationary observer to a mobile explorer, becoming more purposeful in their movements, more expressive in their communication, and more curious about the world around them.</p>

  <p>Developmental milestones are behaviors and physical skills seen in infants as they grow. While every child develops at their own pace, the CDC and AAP provide general timeframes for when most children reach certain milestones.</p>

  <h2>What social and emotional milestones should I expect at 6–9 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 9 months, most babies show clear separation anxiety when a familiar caregiver leaves, recognize familiar faces and prefer them over strangers, and express a range of emotions including joy, frustration, and curiosity (CDC, 2022). These behaviors reflect rapid development of the social brain and the formation of specific attachment relationships.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Separation anxiety:</strong> They may act shy, clingy, or fearful around strangers. They may cry when you leave the room or when a relative tries to hold them. This is a sign of healthy attachment, not a regression.</li>
    <li><strong>Showing preferences:</strong> They have favorite toys and favorite people.</li>
    <li><strong>Emotional expression:</strong> They show a range of emotions, from pure joy and laughter to frustration and anger.</li>
    <li><strong>Mirror recognition:</strong> They enjoy looking at themselves (and you) in the mirror.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What communication milestones should my 6–9 month old reach?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 9 months, most babies babble with repetitive consonant-vowel strings like "ba-ba-ba," "da-da-da," and "ma-ma-ma," respond to their own name, and understand the word "no" (CDC, 2022). Pointing at objects of interest — declarative pointing — also begins to emerge around this age and is an important social communication milestone.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Babbling:</strong> Long repetitive strings of consonant sounds like "pa-pa-pa" and "ba-ba-ba." By 9 months, they often string these together in extended "sentences."</li>
    <li><strong>Name recognition:</strong> They respond to their name and may look when you call them.</li>
    <li><strong>Gestures:</strong> They may start using their fingers to point at things they want or find interesting.</li>
    <li><strong>Copying:</strong> They try to copy the sounds and gestures you make.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What cognitive milestones should I look for at 6–9 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 9 months, most babies understand object permanence — they look for objects they see you hide under a blanket and understand that a toy still exists even when out of sight (CDC, 2022). They also actively explore cause and effect: banging objects together to hear the sound, dropping things to watch them fall, and pressing buttons that make noise.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Object permanence:</strong> They look for objects they saw you hide. This is why peek-a-boo becomes genuinely exciting at this age.</li>
    <li><strong>Exploration:</strong> They use hands and mouth to explore everything. They bang objects together to see what sound they make.</li>
    <li><strong>Cause and effect:</strong> They may drop a toy repeatedly to watch you pick it up — learning that their actions have results.</li>
    <li><strong>Pincer grasp emerging:</strong> Around 9 months, they begin using their thumb and index finger to pick up small things. This fine motor milestone opens the door to self-feeding.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What gross motor milestones should my 6–9 month old be reaching?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 9 months, most babies can sit without support, roll easily in both directions, bear weight on their legs when held standing, and are beginning to crawl, scoot, or army-crawl (CDC, 2022). Some babies pull themselves to a standing position using furniture by 9 months. The progression varies widely — the method of movement matters less than the fact that movement is happening.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Sitting:</strong> They sit without support and can reach for toys while sitting.</li>
    <li><strong>Rolling:</strong> They roll easily in both directions.</li>
    <li><strong>Weight bearing:</strong> When held in a standing position, they support weight on their legs and may bounce.</li>
    <li><strong>Movement:</strong> Many babies begin to crawl, scoot, or army-crawl. Some skip crawling and go directly to pulling up. Both are within the range of typical development.</li>
    <li><strong>Pulling up:</strong> By 9 months, many babies can pull themselves up to a standing position using furniture.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 6–9 Month Milestones</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When should I talk to my pediatrician about my 9-month-old's milestones?</h2>
    <p>The CDC and AAP suggest talking to your pediatrician if your 9-month-old:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does not sit with help</li>
      <li>Does not babble ("mamama," "bababa," "dadada")</li>
      <li>Does not respond to their own name</li>
      <li>Does not seem to recognize familiar people</li>
      <li>Does not look where you point</li>
      <li>Does not transfer toys from one hand to the other</li>
      <li>Has lost skills they once had</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If you have any concerns about your baby's development, do not wait — speak with your pediatrician. Early intervention services are available in every U.S. state for children under age 3 and can begin before a formal diagnosis.</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
